genius_description:
‚ÄúLevel of Concern‚Äù is a ‚Äúsimple but hopeful‚Äù song about Tyler‚Äôs thoughts concerning the effects the coronavirus made on society and the music industry. In the song, Tyler‚Äôs thoughts are presumed to be shared with his wife Jenna as he also asks them for comfort, even if it is a lie.

Inspired to write a song during the pandemic to help the workers in the live music industry, Tyler decided to make his first attempt at writing on an electric guitar. A portion of the single‚Äôs proceeds were donated to Crew Nation, an organization that helps individuals who work in the live performance industry who were laid off during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The song‚Äôs music video shows Tyler and Josh quarantined in their homes with their families, with Tyler‚Äôs then-newborn daughter Rosie appearing in the band‚Äôs media for the first time. Tyler and Josh collaborate on the song and video by mailing the USB drive from the single art back and forth to each other.

Tyler‚Äôs mom inspired him to write a song for their fans in this unprecedented moment in all of our lives. He decided to write about the last time he felt this out of control. This virus has taken such a huge toll on everyone and as a new dad now in lockdown it makes him feel helpless. He chose to turn it into a love song about his wife. He compares this time of little control to that moment when he decided to commit to a life with Jenna & that uneasy feeling of realizing that when you make that kind of a commitment to someone else, you give up a good portion of control. COVID-19, or the coronavirus, is an infectious disease that causes respiratory illness symptoms that are similar to pneumonia. Those suffering from it often experience a cough, fever, or in more serious cases, difficulty breathing. Many citizens all around the world were being encouraged to quarantine themselves in their houses in an attempt to help slow the spread of COVID-19, and with the United States issuing state-wide stay-at-home orders.



The music video for this song shows band members Tyler and Josh quarantined in their houses with their families, pushing the idea that they love spending time with their families despite the social distancing guidelines.

This line could also a pun on the phrase ‚ÄúWould you be my Valentine?‚Äù']])]

genius_description:
‚ÄúJUMP‚Äù features Baby and YoungBoy rapping about their viral success, citing how their music makes people ‚Äújump‚Äù due to the energy and hype surrounding both of their aggressive and trap-filled styles.

The track‚Äôs instrumental is centered around a heavy bass line with a squeaky, electronic instrument providing the melody for the vocals of both rappers.

A music video was released for the track on the same day as its release, featuring similar quarantine themes to those seen on the album‚Äôs cover.
genius_annotations:
[('I get high by myself in the skybox (Yeah)', [['The term ‚Äúskybox‚Äù refers to an expensive and luxurious seating area high within a sports arena. Skyboxes are generally enclosed and offer a private viewing experience, allowing DaBaby to get high on his own in the private and suite-like area.']]), ('(Rocco did it again)', [['Rocco Did It Again! is an American producer best known for his production on YNW Melly and 9lokknine‚Äôs 2018 hit track, ‚Äú223‚Äôs.‚Äú This track marks the first time he‚Äôs worked with either DaBaby or YoungBoy Never Broke Again.']]), ('Made a song in ten minutes, went platinum', [['DaBaby‚Äôs March 2019 track ‚ÄúSuge‚Äù was certified 2x platinum on July 16, 2019.

In an interview with The Breakfast Club, DaBaby revealed that he and the track‚Äôs producer jetsonmade made the song in about ten to fifteen minutes.']]), ('(Hold on, Lil Top, talk to ‚Äôem, nigga)', [['Lil Top is one of YoungBoy‚Äôs nicknames. It is speculated to be his street name because in ‚ÄúIn Control‚Äù he said:

YoungBoy, Lil Top, nigga, bitch nigga, don‚Äôt say Kentrell

YoungBoy also mentioned his nickname Lil Top in the songs ‚ÄúLil Top,‚Äù ‚ÄúTen Talk,‚Äù ‚ÄúFine By Time,‚Äù ‚ÄúHow You Want It‚Äù and more.']]), ('I make it jump like I‚Äôm Giannis (Just honest)', [['Giannis Antetokounmpo is a professional basketball player who, at the time of this song‚Äôs release, was one of the sport‚Äôs most popular young stars. The Greek-born athlete became known for his extremely impressive jumps during games.



DaBaby has also earned a reputation as an electrifying live performer, making the crowd move to his songs while he performs.']]), ('I Kurt Angle that ho, put her leg in the air, ankle lock
 Hold that bitch ‚Äôtil she tap out (Bitch)', [['DaBaby shouts out former WWE wrestler Kurt Angle and pays homage to his submission finisher, The Ankle Lock. The Ankle Lock which is also commonly referred to as The Angle Lock has made many of Angle‚Äôs opponents tap out. Like Angle, DaBaby is able to put his girl into submission.']]), ('Wait a minute, who are you? (Ayy, yo, K.i.D.)', [['This is the producer tag of North Carolina-based producer and frequent Baby collaborator DJ K.i.D. The two have collaborated on multiple songs in the past, including Baby‚Äôs September 2019 hit ‚ÄúINTRO‚Äù and his February 2020 single ‚ÄúSHUT UP.‚Äù

The tag is sampled from a 1989 children‚Äôs program-turned meme titled ‚ÄúYou On Kazoo!‚Äù The tag is sampled from a clip that went viral due to its peculiar nature and tone of voice:

https://youtu.be/cRpdIrq7Rbo?t=15']])]

genius_description:
‚ÄúLosses‚Äù is a track that Drake uses to describe a relationship that went off course. He implies that what he states in this track is undisputable as each verse ends with the line:

I‚Äôm not tryna make no song, these are cold facts

The intro, interlude, and outro on the track are taken from Drake‚Äôs Instagram Live session with his father, Dennis Graham, that occurred on March 21, 2020, amidst the outbreak of COVID-19 and international quarantine efforts used to deter its spread.
genius_annotations:
[('Like I‚Äôm tryna show the waves, this is no cap', [['Drake alludes to not wearing a cap to show off his waves, as a play on words to show that he is not lying ‚Äì as the phrase ‚Äòno cap‚Äô suggests']]), ('Spoiled rotten, they could smell you ‚Äôfore you walked in', [['There is a double meaning here ‚Äì one of a positive connotation and one of a negative connotation.

The negative one, which is what is more associate with the phrase ‚Äúspoiled rotten‚Äù is that she has a bad entitled attitude and everyone knows her by it when she walks in.

The positive connotation, which is less easily detectable, is that Drake has spoiled her with wealth, gifts and fame, that people also know her as a result of that. They can even smell the expensive signature fragrances that she wears and know that it is her before she enters a room.']]), ('I had friends that only had half of they heart in', [['Firstly, it could mean that these people were not fully engaged or committed to the friendship and had ulterior motives.

Secondly, when one is said to not have a heart, among many things, it means they are horrible people. Having half a heart would just be a step below that.']]), ('This life is really something you get lost in', [['As a huge A-list celebrity, Drake lives larger than life and it is easy for someone who is not used to it like the girl he speaks about to get lost in. She gets lost in the fame, the expensive gifts, popularity etc. At the same time, she‚Äôs too focused on it that she has lost herself and as a result Drake has lost her.']]), ('When I visit my last place is the only time I‚Äôm in last place
 See me these days, I never got on a sad face', [['Drake puts a twist on a line from Mike Stud‚Äôs July 2015 song, ‚ÄúThese Days‚Äù:

Only time I‚Äôm second place is when I‚Äôm at my second place']]), ('Like I‚Äôm tryna show the waves, this is no cap', [['Drake uses this line as a double entendre explaining that he enjoys showing off his waves instead of keeping a wave-cap on to keep them fresh.



An infamous selfie of Drake in a wave-cap (a.k.a. a ‚Äúdu-rag‚Äù)

The term ‚Äúno cap‚Äù simply means someone isn‚Äôt lying. Drake then uses the line to say that he is making waves in music and that he isn‚Äôt lying about it.

An example of his trendiness in music is his song ‚ÄúToosie Slide‚Äù that created a dance craze on TikTok, even before the song had released.']]), ('This is not one of them stories that got three sides
 This is not one of them stories you could rewind', [['Drake could be dropping a nod to two storytelling songs‚ÄîJoe Budden‚Äôs December 2005 song, ‚ÄúThree Sides To A Story‚Äù and Nas‚Äò December 2001 song, ‚ÄúRewind.‚Äù

Nas listed Drake as one of his top five current rappers in 2016 while Budden and Drake have had a long history of feuding before squashing their beef on Budden‚Äôs Instagram Live in April 2020.']]), ('I did it by being myself with no dramatic acting
 I couldn‚Äôt sit around and wait, I had to have it happen', [['Before finding fame as a rapper, Drake acted in the  Canadian television show, Degrassi: The Next Generation where he played Jimmy Brooks, a high school basketball star who‚Äôs wheelchair-bound after he was shot by another student. This ties in with the ‚Äúcouldn‚Äôt sit around‚Äù line.



In a 2013 interview with CBC News, Drake spoke about how he doesn‚Äôt have to put on a persona, splitting between his public and private life. He said:

I get to wake up every day, and I don‚Äôt have to think about anything, I just get to go and be myself. I don‚Äôt have to remember to do this, or dress like this, or put on this accent. I just get to wake up and be myself.

In the same interview, when asked about why he chose a career in music over acting he said:

I knew right away, and it had a lot to do with the process of acting. It‚Äôs just so dependent on so many other things other than yourself. It actually takes a long time to get on set and do what you love.']]), ('I never thought I‚Äôd see awards in a glass case
 I could‚Äôve ended up in your crib with a masked face', [['In this line, Drake is talking about the display of his various awards in his Toronto mansion, which was first seen in the music video for his April 2020 hit, ‚ÄúToosie Slide‚Äù:



Continuing this, Drake then claims how his life could have played out entirely different, even to where he may have been a masked man breaking into homes.

This could also be a double entendre for how he and his woman could have quarantined together, as this song was released during the COVID-19 pandemic, which forced citizens around the world to stay at home to protect themselves from the virus.

Also, Drake was pictured in a ski mask in the artwork and music video for ‚ÄúToosie Slide‚Äù and the artwork for Dark Lane Demo Tapes.']]), ('Hey, Instagram

genius_description:
During the difficult and unprecedented times of the COVID-19 pandemic, ‚ÄúSix Feet Apart,‚Äù is a hopeful, yet sad, song by American country music star Luke Combs.

Luke briefly explained the song‚Äôs meaning in the song‚Äôs YouTube video bio:

It‚Äôs about the current times and us looking forward to the day all of this is over. I hope y'all like it.
genius_annotations:
[('Probably over-wash my hands', [['I just wanted to add a little bit of like lightheartedness in there, man. Eventually this thing is going to end and we know it‚Äôs not going to be tomorrow, but it‚Äôs going to end sooner than later. And I think that‚Äôll be something we can laugh about later.']]), ('Watch a ball game from the stands', [['I‚Äôm a huge Carolina Panthers guy. Would definitely love to go see them. I went to Appalachia State.  I think people will be going out and having experiences more after this. Because they‚Äôll realize that it‚Äôs not something that‚Äôs guaranteed, you know? It‚Äôs a privilege to be able to go sit in a sporting arena and watch a NBA game or watch a college basketball game, you know? That‚Äôs something that we get to do. And I think now, we‚Äôre all kind of realizing that it was never something that we were guaranteed.']]), ('Buy my buddies all a round
 Pay some extra on the tab
 Catch a movie, catch a cab', [['At times it can be tough for me to really go do anything. Which is a good thing; I‚Äôm definitely not complaining about that. Because that means things are going well. But my life has just changed in a lot of ways since this all started. So I think it‚Äôs more like, the pay the extra on the tab thing was, obviously there are a lot of people in the restaurant world who are struggling right now, you know? And you know, I‚Äôm a big guy; I like to eat. So I got a lot of respect for those folks that cook some dinner for us and serve for us. So I just feel really lucky to be able to do what I do. I‚Äôve been really blessed financially. And I‚Äôm a big believer in giving that back in any way that I can, you know? Even if it‚Äôs tipping somebody $100 on a $20 check, you know? I enjoy being able to do that and helping somebody who might need it. You know, they might not need it. I don‚Äôt know. But it just always feels like the right thing to do. And I think, after this is all over, that will be something that people should probably do a little bit more of, you know what I mean? Is put an extra five bucks on there if you can. That may help somebody out a lot more than you realize. So that‚Äôs kind of where that whole idea for that specific line came from was just being able to give back in any way that you can.']]), ('First thing that I‚Äôm gonna do

I would really love to do that, because we were about to play a show, and about to do arenas in Dublin, London, and in Glasgow, which would have been really cool. So obviously missed out on that opportunity, but that would be it. But I think it would be really neat to just go to a bar and have a beer too. I know there are some places in the country that are opened up, but I‚Äôm the guy that errs on the side of caution when it comes to that kind of stuff. So being able to do that when it really feels normal again, when it‚Äôs just a carefree thing, I think would be interesting. Because I could probably pop down the street and get a beer at a bar right now if I wanted to, but that just doesn‚Äôt seem like the right thing to do to me right now. So I think doing that when you don‚Äôt have to worry about it is going to be really nice.']]), ('It‚Äôs a mystery, I suppose

 And there will be light after dark

I‚Äôm not a trained medical professional, so I can‚Äôt go out and help people in that sense. I‚Äôve donated some money to some various causes, which has been a great thing. But I think just being hopeful is all I really have right now, you know what I mean? I mean, obviously you got your friends and family, and your loved ones, and stuff, to hold on to in these times.But I don‚Äôt know, I don‚Äôt think anybody knows. It‚Äôs a wait-and-see environment. And doing what musicians do, I think that‚Äôs going to be one of the last things that opens back up. It‚Äôs not going to be like tomorrow, they‚Äôre going to be like, ‚ÄúMan virus is down 1%, so let‚Äôs have a show with 20,000 people.‚Äù So in that sense it can be defeating, but it‚Äôs also you know that eventually it will happen. You just know, and that you have this ability and this platform to go out and do something that you super happy. And something that makes a lot of other people super happy, and enjoy their night, or their week, or whatever it is. That‚Äôs a really great feeling, and not getting to do that is tough because you don‚Äôt write songs for yourself to sit around and listen to. I enjoy writing songs and I enjoy singing, but I do it for other people.']]), ('I miss my mom, I miss my dad', [['I miss a lot of stuff about my parents. I miss seeing them. ‚ÄúSocial Distancing‚Äú is a standout track off of the deluxe of My Turn. On the track, Lil Baby uses the current social distancing recommendation ‚Äì due to the COVID-19 pandemic ‚Äì as a metaphor to emphasize how far ahead of the competition he is. Dropping references to expensive items and rich girls, Baby boasts about his lifestyle with fame.

On April 14, Baby teased the track by tweeting a line from the track:

https://twitter.com/lilbaby4PF/status/1250086899659702278?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw

genius_description:
‚ÄúStuck with U‚Äù is a collaboration inspired by the global lockdown due to the 2020 Coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak. All sales and streams from this song will proceed to First Responders Children‚Äôs Foundation, which supports grants and scholarships for children of the front lines and essential workers during the global pandemic.

Rumors of the collaboration arose when Scooter Braun, Ariana and Justin‚Äôs manager, shared a tweet with both artists' name tagged on May 1, 2020. Bieber shared the instrumental on Instagram later that day and asked fans to participate and tweet prom videos. On May 2, 2020, Grande officially announced the collaboration on Twitter.

genius_description:
‚ÄúGOOBA‚Äù is the first single from Brooklyn rapper 6ix9ine since his infamous September 2019 testimony in the case of United States vs. Nine Trey Bloods. The track comes just weeks after his April 2020 compassionate early release due to the 2020 SARS-CoV-2 outbreak in America.

On the track, 6ix9ine addresses many of the people who negatively commented on how he dealt with his charges in the aforementioned court case and his early release.

Rumors of the track first began on April 29, 2020 when it was confirmed that Tekashi sought and received permission from federal judges to shoot a music video in the backyard of his residence. On May 7, 2020, billboards in Times Square confirmed the release of an upcoming single the next day, which ended up being ‚ÄúGOOBA.‚Äù

The song broke the record of most viewed hip-hop video within 24 hours, which was previously set by Eminem.
genius_annotations:
[('Now we catch him at the chicken spot, up a couple chops', [["Chicken spot, according to Urban Dictionary, is usually a slang term used by people to refer to any chicken restaurant that isn‚Äôt a KFC franchise, however it could also be a reference to The Chicken Spot, a restaurant that was created by Chris Veso, the CEO of Queens Hospitality, that has its headquarters in Queens, New York, which is also the birthplace of 6ix9ine.

‚Äò'Chop‚Äô‚Äò is a slang term for talk."]]), ('D√≠melo, mami
 Fresca, you nasty', [['‚ÄúD√≠melo‚Äù translates to ‚Äútell it to me,‚Äù while ‚Äúmami,‚Äù literally meaning ‚Äúlittle mama,‚Äù is an affectionate term for a female partner like ‚Äúbaby girl‚Äù in English.

‚ÄúFresca,‚Äù sometimes pronounced ‚Äúfreca,‚Äù is a term in Spanish that can literally be translated as ‚Äúfresh,‚Äù but is often used in a sexual context, describing a woman who will easily have sex, and can be used as a pejorative like ‚Äúslut‚Äù in English.']]), ('Niggas always wanna chase clout, bitch, I am clout', [['6ix9ine defines himself as clout incarnate, and not for nothing either: shortly after the release of ‚ÄúGOOBA‚Äù, he started an Instagram Live video which quickly garnered an audience of over 2,000,000 viewers, breaking the record for most Instagram Live viewers at a time, which had previously been held by Bad Bunny, with 350,000 viewers. He boasted about the feat on Twitter:

https://twitter.com/6ix9ine/status/1258851646794166272

Various outlets and fellow artists, including Blueface and Meek Mill, have described his antics as ‚Äúclout chasing‚Äù behavior.

The reasons for his clout are varied, but it‚Äôs undeniable that 6ix9ine has steadily remained in the headlines and in people‚Äôs mouths since his debut, for better or for worse. Whether it be for his numerous public feuds with high-profile celebrities, his noted criminal history, his loud, colorful appearance coupled with his brash, aggressive, ‚Äúvillain-like‚Äù persona or, most notably, his involvement with and subsequent testifying against the Nine Trey Bloods, he‚Äôs gone anything but unnoticed by the media and the general public for the better part of two years.']]), ('Slide, slide in the Bentley truck-a, the Wraith truck-a', [['During 6ix9ine‚Äôs Instagram Live video following the release of ‚ÄúGOOBA‚Äù, he revealed that he had purchased several cars shortly after being released from prison, including a Rolls Royce Wraith and a Range Rover.']]), ('I tell a nigga don‚Äôt dick ride, don‚Äôt blick ride
 Leave it to the double thick thighs, twin sisters', [['A ‚Äúblicky‚Äù (or, as it‚Äôs abbreviated here, ‚Äúblick‚Äù) is New York slang for a pistol, and a term 6ix9ine infamously used in his breakout single ‚ÄúGUMMO‚Äù:

Niggas iffy, uh, blicky got the stiffy, uh
Got the blicky, uh, drum, it hold fifty, uh

Furthermore, an extended clip is also called a ‚Äúdick‚Äù in slang. In this context, blick can also refer to his penis, similar to the way he used it on ‚ÄúTATI‚Äù:

Licky licky, licky on my blicky, uh

The ‚Äútwin sisters‚Äù in question are Rachel ‚ÄúJade‚Äù Watley, a model and bartender who has been 6ix9ine‚Äôs girlfriend since late 2018, and her sister Sara ‚ÄúBaddie Gi‚Äù Watley, both of whom appear in the song‚Äôs video.



The two gained notoriety in October 2018 following a public altercation with Cardi B and members of her entourage at the Angels Strip Club in Flushing, Queens, New York, where both sisters worked as bartenders, which began after Cardi accused Jade of sleeping with her husband, Offset.']]), ('DayDay made that nigga Diddy Bop, cha-cha-cha-cha-cha', [['The Diddy Bop is a dance named after its creator Diddy, a rapper also known as Puff Daddy. 6ix9ine has referred to the dance before in his song ‚ÄúKEKE‚Äù, saying:

Double trigger Glock (Ah), make him Diddy Bop, boy (Ayy)']]), ('Are you dumb, stupid, or dumb, huh?
 Play me like a dummy, like bitch, are you dumb?
 Are you dumb, stupid, or dumb, huh?', [['Here, 6ix9ine interpolates a line from one of his most popular songs, ‚ÄúSTOOPID‚Äù:

Bozo, bitch, are you dumb-d-dumb-dumb-dumb-d-dumb-dumb-dumb? (Stupid)

The lyric was originally borrowed from the track ‚ÄúAre You Dumb‚Äù by Ronny Godz and Dboy Lo.

The line ‚ÄúPlay me like a dummy‚Äù may also be about 6ix9ine‚Äôs debut studio album Dummy Boy, released in late 2018 or to the slang ‚ÄúAre you crazy, are you stupid, are you dumb?‚Äù originating from Toronto and later popularized by rappers like Drake and Chromazz.

In early 2019, after a surprise appearance at the Grammy Awards, Drake used this expression on backstage after receiving the Grammy for best rap song.

https://youtu.be/MXFGZgoOMTI?t=66']]), ('They sick, been hot way before coronavirus', [['6ix9ine has been a trending artist for the past few years before a strain of the coronavirus sparked a global pandemic in 2020. The virus helped 6ix9ine get out of prison early due to health concerns from his asthma.

This line is most likely a play on words with ‚Äúsick‚Äù and the coronavirus, with ‚Äúhot‚Äù relating to the fever someone may have when they contract the sickness.']]), ('(Jah, ayy, you know that boy)', [['This is the producer tag for Jahnei Clarke. This is the first collaboration between Jahnei and Tekashi 6ix9ine.

Jahnei Clarke has produced for many other artists as well, such as Masego, TrifeDrew, Ski Mask the Slump God, and many more.']]), ('As-salam-alam alaykum, you big hater', [['‚ÄòAs-salƒÅmu alaykum‚Äô is a greeting in Arabic that means ‚ÄúPeace be upon you‚Äù.

The ‚Äòsalam‚Äô is a religious salutation among Muslims when greeting, though it is also used by Arabic speakers of other religions, such as Arab Christians.']])]

On ‚ÄúSolitaires,‚Äù Future reunites with Travis Scott on a song in which they trade boastful bars about their luxurious lifestyles, from the luxury fashion brands they can afford to the jewelry and cars they own. They also drop bars on the COVID-19 pandemic, an ongoing disease at the time of this song‚Äôs release, to compare their diamonds.

This song‚Äôs instrumental is produced by Wheezy, who frequently produces songs for Future. It is also co-produced by MIKE DEAN, who frequently produces songs for Travis.

A snippet of this song surfaced to the public a few hours before its release of Future playing the song in the studio with Travis.

DJ Screw is a legendary hip-hop artist from Houston, Texas, who is best known for pioneering the chopped and screwed technique. The chopped and screwed scene was closely connected with lean, both emerging in Houston at the same time, with each contributing to the popularity of the other. ‚ÄúX‚Äù marks the Jonas Brothers' first collaboration with Colombian singer-songwriter KAROL G. The song was released concurrently with the boys' other song, ‚ÄúFive More Minutes.‚Äù Both tracks make up their two pack bundle titled XV.

Similar to the brothers' January 2020 single ‚ÄúWhat a Man Gotta Do,‚Äù is an upbeat vibe, which is also Bollywood-inspired.

The official music video for this song premiered to the band‚Äôs YouTube channel three days after its release, on May 18, 2020. Everybody in the video is shown dancing on video camera on separate iPhones. This was because the COVID-19 pandemic, was going on at the time of its release, which killed a lot of people worldwide. To take appropriate action, people were predominantly quarantined in their own homes.

genius_description:
Marking the start of a new era, ‚ÄúDaisies‚Äù is a self-empowerment anthem by American singer-songwriter Katy Perry. Shortly after the track‚Äôs release, Katy took to her social media platforms to share the inspiration behind the song:

I wrote this song a couple [of] months ago as a call to remain true to the course you‚Äôve set for yourself, regardless of what others may think.

She then elaborated on how the song has ‚Äútaken a new meaning [for her]‚Äù after parts of the world went into a lockdown due to the COVID-19 pandemic.

Unlike her past lead singles which tend to be more upbeat and bubbly, ‚ÄúDaisies‚Äù features a mid-tempo production in its verses and a guitar in its chorus. This is also Katy‚Äôs first time working with The Monsters & Strangerz ‚Äî an American production and songwriting team who has previously worked on hits like January 2018‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Middle.‚Äù
genius_annotations:
[('I‚Äôm the Hail Mary', [['A Hail Mary is a football play where the quarterback attempts to throw a last-minute long pass to score. It‚Äôs typically unsuccessful, and is often used as a last resort, but when it works, it‚Äôs a huge game-changer and proves the tenacity of the team.

Drawing this comparison, Katy shows how far she‚Äôll go to fight for herself, even if her plans seem out of reach.']]), ('I‚Äôm the small town
 One in seven billion
 Why can‚Äôt it be me?', [['The towns represent the people out of the world. Others may laugh at her, but as she is one of the many, she has the same chance to rise as everyone.']]), ('They told me I was out there, tried to knock me down
 Took those sticks and stones, showed ‚Äôem I could build a house', [['‚ÄúSticks and Stones‚Äù is an English children‚Äôs rhyme that dates back to the 1800s in response to verbal bullying. It promotes the idea of anti-bullying and standing up against name-calling. The original rhyme is:

Sticks and stones may break my bones
But words will never hurt me.

This is not the first time Katy has referenced the rhyme in her music. On February 2012‚Äôs ‚ÄúPart of Me,‚Äù she sings:

Throw your sticks and your stones
Throw your bombs and your blows
But you‚Äôre not gonna break my soul

On ‚ÄúDaisies,‚Äù Katy Perry adds a twist to the well-known rhyme by detailing how she used the ‚Äústicks and stones‚Äù thrown at her to grow as a person.

Fans have noted that Katy could also be alluding to a line from June 2019‚Äôs ‚ÄúYou Need To Calm Down‚Äù by American singer-songwriter Taylor Swift where she sings:

And snakes and stones never broke my bones

Both Katy and Taylor had a well-documented infamous feud back in 2014 due to some issues related to the dancers for their tours in December of 2013. Years later, the pair made up and Katy appeared in the music video for the aforementioned track.



Katy Perry and Taylor Swift on a music video set back in early 2019.


Perry subtly teased this line back in early May before the song was even announced to promote a pair of shoes ‚Äî which featured daisies on it ‚Äî by her footwear store Katy Perry Collections. She captioned the post:

Sticks and stones may break your bones, but Daisies are the friendliest flower']]), ('When did we all stop believing in magic?', [['This line was first teased by Katy via her social media platforms on May 12, 2020.

Alongside the teaser, Perry also shared a picture of her in front of the set of the song‚Äôs music video as she proudly shows off her baby bump.

The singer-songwriter first revealed that she‚Äôs expecting a daughter with actor Orlando Bloom on a ballad preceding ‚ÄúDaisies‚Äù titled ‚ÄúNever Worn White‚Äù released on March 5, 2020.']]), ('I‚Äôm the long shot', [['‚ÄúLong Shot‚Äù is the title of a song Katy recorded before her rise to fame with her debut album, One of the Boys. The song was later covered by Kelly Clarkson in 2009, for her album All I Ever Wanted.']]), ('They tell me that I‚Äôm crazy, but I‚Äôll never let ‚Äôem change me
 ‚ÄôTil they cover me in daisies, daisies, daisies', [['Katy will keep being who she is until ‚Äúshe is covered in daisies‚Äù, that is, until she dies.

On May 12, 2020, Katy took to Instagram to share a post with this line as its caption alongside a picture of a yellow daisy.

‚ÄúTROLLZ‚Äù is the second single from rapper 6ix9ine since he was released from prison early to finish his sentence in home confinement.

The track was first mentioned on his Instagram on May 23, 2020, when he claimed it would be out six days later and the post‚Äôs most liked comment would be the song title. This turned out to be his own suggestion of the decided name. The release was then pushed back to June 12 in support of the black community and the protests that broke out due to the killing of George Floyd. 6ix9ine stated this was ‚Äúout of respect for what we are going through right now.‚Äù

‚ÄúTROLLZ‚Äù takes the shape of a catchy, fast-paced trap beat that features uncharacteristically soft vocals from 6ix9ine on the chorus and the quintessential Minaj formula of a verse packed full of wordplay and a sung section.

genius_description:
‚ÄúThe Bigger Picture‚Äù is a protest song from Lil Baby, featuring the rapper commenting on police brutality and systemic racism in America in the wake of the murder of George Floyd.

The track comes just days after Baby went out and protested on the streets of Atlanta on June 8, 2020. At the protest, Baby was a leading force, leading the crowd on his bicycle (as depicted on the single‚Äôs cover art) as well as handing out protestors supplies and money and speaking in front of the crowd when they reached the march‚Äôs destination of Georgia‚Äôs State Capitol Building.
genius_annotations:
[('They trainin‚Äô officers to kill us, then shootin‚Äô protestors with these rubber bullets', [['Although police officers in the United States are not explicitly trained to kill African Americans, several factors contribute to the continuation of police brutality against African Americans. The main reason is racial bias: racial profiling has been prevalent for centuries and continues to happen today, with countless stories of detainments, investigations, arrests, and convictions based on the color of the suspect‚Äôs skin. It is also well known that some U.S. police departments have a culture of prioritizing the protection of their officers over civilians. This protection enables officers to commit brutality without fear of consequence.

In this line, Lil Baby emphasizes that police continue to use excessive force against demonstrators protesting police brutality.

When protests ensued after the murder of George Floyd, some police departments responded with police donning riot gear and crowd control measures such as rubber bullets. Some states mobilized their national guard to respond to large gatherings that had the potential of becoming unlawful assemblies.

For example, on June 1, 2020, demonstrators gathered in Washington D.C., near the White House for a largely peaceful protest. However, at 6:30 p.m., 30 minutes before curfew, several federal law enforcement agencies in riot gear advanced on crowds, using brute force, flash bangs, tear gas, and rubber bullets to disperse the legal assembly.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JxYmILDya0A

During the police‚Äôs advancements on the protestors, Australian viewers watched in horror as an Australian 7NEWS crew was assaulted live on television. An armored policeman struck the cameraman in the gut with a shield and another policeman hit the reporter‚Äôs backpack with a baton.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wkf-znzWKRc

This line points out the irony of police using excessive force (as seen in the videos) during a protest against that same brutality.']]), ('It‚Äôs too many mothers that‚Äôs grieving
 They killing us for no reason
 Been going on for too long to get even', [['Black and African American people have undergone 400+ years of discrimination in the United States. Slavery, until 1865 when the 13th Amendment was passed. And after the ending of slavery, they have undergone de jure (legal) and de facto (in practice) discrimination. Legal discrimination (more commonly known as segregation or Jim Crow laws) on race ended with the passing of the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

In conclusion, 400+ years of historical wrongs cannot really be corrected to ever ‚Äúget even‚Äù. There is much debate on what could/should be done this article covers the proposal of reparations, which is one of the many suggestions.

‚ÄúThey killing us for no reason‚Äù can be seen in the many harrowing stories of killings of Black people, whether that be by police or racist people; for example, the lynchings that happened throughout the 19th and 20th centuries.

One of the most high-profile cases of this was the murder of Ahmaud Arbery which was A clear-cut case of racial profiling. Where Ahmaud was confronted for jogging through a neighborhood by two men with a shotgun. genius_description:
On ‚ÄúTommy Lee,‚Äù Tyla Yaweh recruits close friend Post Malone. The two sing over a modern hip-hop beat with their melodic flow. They talk about living life with joy without any fears, always keeping hope for the best, and never giving up on life. The song‚Äôs title is a reference to the musician Tommy Lee, a famous drummer of the american rock bands, M√∂tley Cr√ºe and Methods of Mayhem.

Surprisingly, this marks the first collaboration between the two. Tyla has opened for Post‚Äôs Runaway Tour from September 2019 to December 2019. This tour was supposed to end in July 2020, but was cut short due to the COVID-19 pandemic, which was going on at the time of this song‚Äôs release.

genius_description:
‚ÄúBLACK PARADE‚Äù is a song celebrating blackness. It was released in the final hours of Juneteenth, the oldest nationally celebrated commemoration of the end of slavery in the United States.

On the track, Beyonc√© proudly sings about her heritage, hometown, womanhood, and complexion. She also talks about returning to her African roots.

According to her official website, the proceeds of ‚ÄúBLACK PARADE‚Äù will go to the BeyGOOD Black Business Impact Fund. The fund is administered by the National Urban League and will be used to support black-owned small businesses in need.

This is Beyonc√©‚Äôs second release of 2020, after she featured on Megan Thee Stallion‚Äôs ‚ÄúSavage Remix‚Äù in April.
genius_annotations:
[('Nip that lip like lipo (Lipo)', [['This line might refer to a mother giving their teat to a child to suck. It is clearly from the mother‚Äôs perspective, because the ‚Äúnip‚Äù (the maternal, providing body part) executes the action, while the lip (the juvenile, receiving body part) is the object of the sentence. Thus, this phrase enforces the song‚Äôs significant themes of motherhood, aligning with the presence of terms like ‚Äúmama‚Äù and ‚Äúmotherhood.‚Äù The comparison to ‚Äúlipo‚Äù ‚Äî liposuction ‚Äî is principally a play-on-words, but also implies that the mother is made more beautiful by providing for her children.']]), ('Need peace and reparation for my people (Woo)', [['Beyonc√© joins the call for the payment of reparations‚Äîa form of monetary compensation for past harms done. Reparations paid towards marginalized groups in the U.S.‚Äîspecifically descendants of enslaved persons‚Äîhave entered into the mainstream conversation of U.S. politics, even appearing on several Democratic primary stages. A major contributor to cultural consciousness around the need for reparations among recent years, Ta-Nehisi Coates made a compelling argument for reparations in his ‚ÄúA Case For Reparations‚Äù:

To celebrate freedom and democracy while forgetting America‚Äôs origins in a slavery economy is patriotism √† la carte. Perhaps no statistic better illustrates the enduring legacy of our country‚Äôs shameful history of treating black people as sub-citizens, sub-Americans, and sub-humans than the wealth gap. Reparations would seek to close this chasm. But as surely as the creation of the wealth gap required the cooperation of every aspect of the society, bridging it will require the same.']]), ('I charge my crystals in a full moon', [['African people were the first to use crystals, primarily as a decorative material for their bodies, along with other objects from the Mother Nature.

Nowadays, believes and religions use semiprecious rocks (i.e. crystals like amethyst and quartz) in metaphysical purposes, such as healing and energizing processes.

The full moon is a very important symbol in the esoteric believes, referred as a feminine entity, acting as a cleansing and energizing element to the crystals, very useful for someone as demanded as Beyonc√©.']]), ('Hol‚Äô up, don‚Äôt I smell like such a nag champa incense?', [['Nag Champa is a popular fragrance of incense originating from India. It has a sweet sandalwood scent and is also used in soap, essential oils, and candles.']]), ('Stroll line to the barbeque', [['A stroll line is a line of synchronized dancers at an event that are usually all from the same Greek letter organization. DO NOT TRY TO WALK IN BETWEEN THEM, it is offensive. Here is some deeper background on strolling.

Though Beyonc√© is not Greek herself, she has shown major support for black Greek life and HBCU culture in her Homecoming Coachella performance and Netflix documentary.

Beyonc√© paid homage to the rich history and culture of these organizations in her homecoming performance, especially in the ‚Äúbug-a-boo‚Äù section where she had male dancers pretending to be pledged by her and her female dancers.

Stroll lines are how Greeks identify themselves at functions and events. They can be seen making their way through the outskirts of a party or right in the middle! Supposedly, Michael claimed that the phrase was Swahili in order to avoid paying royalties, but Dibango filed a lawsuit and the two ended up settling out of court. According to a 2009 The Guardian article, Dibango‚Äôs lawyers sued again when Rihanna used the same sample without his permission on her September 2007 hit single, ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt Stop the Music."']]), ('Curtis Mayfield on the speaker (Woo)', [['Curtis Mayfield was an African American soul singer, composer, and producer, especially well known for his July 1972 Super Fly soundtrack. The way he explored the struggles of Black America also helped to contribute to the Civil Rights movement.

genius_description:
Accompanied by the release of her project written and recorded during the lockdown due to COVID-19, ‚Äúcardigan‚Äù is the lead single from Taylor Swift‚Äôs eighth studio album, folklore.

Its music video ‚Äî which was written and directed by Taylor and shot during the COVID-19 pandemic ‚Äî finds Taylor shifting through different places by the magic of playing the piano. She revealed in a Tweet that everyone who was on-set took extra precautions to prevent the spread of the virus:

The entire shoot was overseen by a medical inspector, everyone wore masks, stayed away from each other, and I even did my own hair, makeup, and styling.

‚Äúcardigan‚Äù is believed to be the first part of folklore‚Äôs ‚ÄúTeenage Love Triangle,‚Äù told from the point of view of Betty. The storyline is followed by ‚Äúaugust‚Äù and ‚Äúbetty.‚Äù Swift explained in a livechat the night of folklore‚Äôs release:

There‚Äôs a collection of three songs I refer to as The Teenage Love Triangle. These three songs explore a love triangle from all three people‚Äôs perspectives at different times in their lives.
genius_annotations:
[('The smell of smoke would hang around this long', [['Before folklore, Swift‚Äôs last mention of smoke in her work was on her 2019 track ‚ÄúDaylight,‚Äù where she likens it to consequences for her actions or beliefs:

I wounded the good and I trusted the wicked
Clearing the air, I breathed in the smoke

As a whole, ‚ÄúDaylight‚Äù describes her experiences with fame and how things started looking up after her reputation era. However, she still experiences self-doubt and insecurity about what she‚Äôs gone through in the spotlight, which she describes on folklore tracks like ‚Äúpeace‚Äù and ‚Äúhoax,‚Äù as well as ‚Äúlong story short,‚Äù which appears on folklore‚Äôs sister album, evermore:

I fell from the pedestal
Right down the rabbithole
Long story short, it was a bad time']]), ('Leavin‚Äô like a father', [["Here Taylor makes use of an ironic simile, a rhetorical device developed by comparing a situation to an opposite idea such as a father, meant to be a permanent, integral part of child‚Äôs life, leaving. The overall effect saddens the tone and parallels just how betrayed Betty felt at James' unfaithfulness.

Taylor makes use of another, similar ironic simile on her 2012 track ‚ÄúAll Too Well‚Äù singing,

And you call me up again just to break me like a promise"]]), ('But I knew you‚Äôd linger like a tattoo kiss', [['Swift previously used the metaphor of a lingering kiss on her 2010 track ‚ÄúLast Kiss,‚Äù but ‚Äútattoo kiss‚Äù makes the impact feel more permanent:

Your name forever the name on my lips
Just like our last kiss

Taylor used to wear temporary tattoos pretty often during her Fearless era, and she used tattoos as a metaphor for someone‚Äôs impact on her on 2017‚Äôs ‚ÄúDress‚Äù:

There is an indentation in the shape of you
Made your mark on me, a golden tattoo

The ‚Äúgolden tattoo‚Äù is a metaphor for her relationship with Joe Alwyn, her boyfriend as of the song‚Äôs release who co-wrote several songs on folklore. They supposedly met at the May 2016 Met Gala, and in October of that year, Taylor was seen wearing golden temporary tattoos to Drake‚Äôs birthday party.']]), ('Playing hide-and-seek and', [['‚Äòhide and seek‚Äô  refers to the two-timing nature of secret relationships, suggesting Betty already knew something was wrong before being told. It could also refer to James playing hard to get by ignoring her all week and then giving her his undivided attention on the weekends.

Furthermore, Taylor has released eight different covers for the deluxe edition of her ‚Äòfolklore‚Äô album, all with different designs and titles, which have been inspired by some of her lyrics. One of these deluxe editions is named ‚Äúhide-and-seek‚Äù.']]), ('Steppin‚Äô on the last train', [['This lyric parallels sentiments found in Swift‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Archer‚Äù from her album Lover, where Swift expresses her aversion to commit in relationships using similar imagery:

Easy they come, easy they go
I jump from the train, I ride off alone

‚ÄúThe last train‚Äù is usually the final train before service stops for the night. This line serves as a metaphor for making a last ditch effort to exit a place or situation one doesn‚Äôt want to be in. This further highlights the hurt that Betty feels, watching James make a conscious choice not to be with her.']]), ('Tried to change the ending', [["Taylor refers to the ending of a relationship like that of a piece of  fiction again during this album in the song ‚Äúexile‚Äù:

I think I‚Äôve seen this film before
And I didn‚Äôt like the ending

It‚Äôs also present much earlier in her discography in the song ‚ÄúBreathe‚Äù from Fearless:

Music starts playin' like the end of a sad movie,
It‚Äôs the kinda ending you don‚Äôt really wanna see

This concept is also featured in ‚ÄúNew Year‚Äôs Day‚Äù from Reputation although in a more positive manner:

Don‚Äôt read the last page
But I stay when it‚Äôs hard or it‚Äôs wrong or we‚Äôre making mistakes"]]), ('Chasin‚Äô shadows in the grocery line', [['‚ÄúChasing shadows‚Äù is a British phrase used to describe someone looking for something that doesn‚Äôt exist or trying to achieve something that is impossible. It seems that Betty is looking for James everywhere she goes even though she knows he isn‚Äôt there. This is similar to line from the previous song ‚Äúthe 1‚Äù:

I thought I saw you at the bus stop, I didn‚Äôt though

The phrase also plays on the Peter Pan reference earlier in the song. In the film Peter and Wendy chase down Peter‚Äôs shadow so they can reattach it. Taylor pairs the juvenile idea of chasing shadows like in Peter Pan with the adult task of grocery shopping to suggest that Betty is growing out of her youthful naivety.






This isn‚Äôt the first time Taylor has evoked the magic mundanity of grocery stores in her lyrics. In ‚ÄúStay Stay Stay‚Äù on her 2012 studio album Red she sings:

You carry my groceries and now I‚Äôm always laughing
And I love you, because you have given me no choice but to
Stay, stay, stay

‚ÄúStay Stay Stay‚Äù depicted a younger Taylor‚Äôs idea of what a true, healthy romantic relationship would look like; everyday activities such as grocery shopping can become filled with fun and wonder when done with someone special.']]), ('Vintage tee, brand new phone', [['This line uses the literary device of juxtaposition, placing two contrasting ideas in close proximity, to imply that the relationships we assume exist between age (vintage/new, young/old) and ‚Äúknowing‚Äù are not as clear-cut as they may seem.

The stanza also details Taylor‚Äôs past four musical and personal eras. ‚ÄúVintage tee, brand new phone‚Äù references the RED era, in which her instagram focused on a hipster aesthetic. ‚ÄúHigh heels on cobblestones‚Äù points to her love for the Tribeca area of New York City, where she lived during her 1989 era. She references reputation in ‚ÄúSequin smile, black lipstick,‚Äù  as evidenced in her 2016 Met Gala look. Finally, "Sensual politics‚Äù refers to the Lover era, where she became a more outspoken voice both in politics and in her romance with Joe Alwyn.']]), ('‚ÄôCause I knew everything when I was young', [['This lyric is an inversion of a lyric repeated earlier in the song:

When you are young they assume you know nothing

Here, Betty rejects the idea that young people know nothing ‚Äì  James expressed this sentiment on the chorus of ‚Äúbetty,‚Äù where he tries to win Betty back after cheating on her:

I‚Äôm only seventeen, I don‚Äôt know anything

It‚Äôs worth noting the retrospective nature of this line, implying Betty is looking back on her relationship with James. Swift explained the song‚Äôs context in the folklore album foreword:

A cardigan that still bears the scent of loss twenty years later.

Swift may have been inspired by poet Oscar Wilde, who once said ‚Äúthe old believe everything, the middle-aged suspect everything, the young know everything.‚Äù However, it‚Äôs also plausible she took inspiration from The Admirable Crichton by J.M. Barrie, the author of Peter Pan:

I‚Äôm not young enough to know everything.']]), ('And I knew you‚Äôd come back to me
 You‚Äôd come back to me
 And you‚Äôd come back to me
 And you‚Äôd come back', [["The idea of a lover coming back is prominent throughout Swift‚Äôs discography, appearing on songs like 2010‚Äôs ‚ÄúIf This Was a Movie‚Äù and 2012‚Äôs ‚ÄúCome Back‚Ä¶ Be Here.‚Äù She words it similarly on her October 2014 track ‚ÄúThis Love,‚Äù which describes an on-and-off relationship:

These hands had to let it go free
And this love came back to me

Later on ‚Äúbetty,‚Äù this sureness is juxtaposed with James' worries, which mirrors how Betty ‚Äúknew everything when [she] was young.‚Äù

But if I just showed up at your party
Would you have me? Would you want me?

It‚Äôs also worth noting all the Peter Pan references throughout the song, most prominently with ‚ÄúPeter losing Wendy.‚Äù In the 1953 animated Disney version, Wendy says a similar line:

Peter Pan! Oh, Peter! I knew you‚Äôd come back."]])]

‚Äúthe 1,‚Äù the second single from the album, centers around the nostalgic remembrance of myths and lost loves. Taylor contemplates an alternate life in which her old wishes had ‚Äúcome true‚Äù and resulted in a relationship with an ex-lover.

Sharing a similar sentiment to Swift‚Äôs track ‚ÄúI Almost Do‚Äù from October 2012‚Äôs Red, ‚Äúthe 1‚Äù is a callback to the folk moments from the same record, folk music being a defining influence on folklore.
genius_annotations:
[('You meet some woman on the internet and take her home', [['Online romance is challenging because oftentimes the lovers live in different places or have different backgrounds. Swift‚Äôs ex is clearly desperate to find a rebound if his, her, or their only strategy for finding romantic partners is using an online dating service or social media. The Internet is also probably how Swift found out about her ex‚Äôs new lover‚Äìthis person could have posted about the new relationship on social media. Taylor is implying that her ex is dating random wymyn they meet online in order to numb the pain of breaking up with the narrator. It also shows that she‚Äôs not moved on yet and she might be jealous thinking he can date other people.

The online themes of this song are also relevant to the times it was released in. It came out in 2020, when everything had moved online due to COVID-19. Whether or not this song is set during COVID, it definitely fits the times.']]), ('I hit the ground running each night', [['To ‚Äúhit the ground running‚Äù means to rush with enthusiasm right out of the gates, which may be an acknowledgement of Swift‚Äôs emotional behavior in romantic relationships.

She also used this phrase on her 2013 song ‚ÄúSweeter Than Fiction,‚Äù which describes someone making their dreams come true:

They never saw it coming
You hit the ground running
And now you‚Äôre onto something']]), ('I, I, I persist and resist the temptation to ask you', [['Swift also wrote about resisting reaching out to an ex on her 2012 song ‚ÄúI Almost Do‚Äù:

It takes everything in me not to call you
And I just wanna run to you
And I hope you know that every time I don‚Äôt
I almost do']]), ('And if my wishes came true', [['A callback to the previous line ‚Äì tossing coins into a pool (more often, a fountain) is said to be a way of making a wish.

This tradition has been passed down through the generations ‚Äì in the days when clean water was a precious gift from the gods, offerings would be left near fountains. Today, we‚Äôve modernized this ancient ritual, throwing money in exchange for a wish come true. This is a perfect example of folklore, which is the theme of the album ‚Äì just one of the millions of ways that stories from people we‚Äôll never know bleed into our own lives and imaginations.']]), ('And if my wishes came true', [['A callback to the previous line ‚Äì tossing coins into a pool (more often, a fountain) is said to be a way of making a wish.

With the phrase ‚Äúanother time,‚Äù she admits that she has, not once, but on multiple occasions, dug out these memories. If Swift is singing as herself, this could suggest that this is not the first song she recorded for the One.

The line‚Äôs morbid imagery is echoed on the album‚Äôs fifth track, ‚Äúmy tears ricochet‚Äù, which also uses death as a metaphor for the end of a relationship.

if I‚Äôm dead to you, why are you at the wake?']]), ('I thought I saw you at the bus stop, I didn‚Äôt though', [['Swift sings this very casually ‚Äî she‚Äôs trying to sound as though she‚Äôs completely moved on, and is looking for small talk, but she shows her hand here. genius_description:
‚Äúbetty‚Äù touches on the aftermath of ‚Äúaugust,‚Äù which describes a summer love that was doomed from the start. Listeners learn that while the summer affair was going on, the speaker, James, was still dating their classmate, Betty.

The song takes a more feminist approach, portraying the narrator as a person named James who can‚Äôt own up to their mistakes, all while Betty flourishes on her own and recognizes her worth.

Sonically, the song exudes a strong sense of nostalgia, delivering production and instrumentals reminiscent to Taylor‚Äôs earlier projects like Fearless and Speak Now, both of which were records written by Taylor in her similarly na√Øve adolescence.

‚Äúbetty‚Äù is believed to be the third part of folklore‚Äôs ‚ÄúTeenage Love Triangle,‚Äù told from the point of view of James. The storyline is preceded by ‚Äúcardigan‚Äù and ‚Äúaugust.‚Äù

Interestingly, James' gender is never explicitly stated‚ÄîJames and Inez (mentioned in the pre-chorus) are, in fact, the names of Blake Lively and Ryan Reynolds‚Äò eldest daughters‚Äîleading some to believe that James could be a girl and that the Teenage Love Triangle is, in fact, a sapphic love story.

However, Taylor confirmed James' gender while explaining the song on country radio:

[James] has lost the love of his life basically and doesn‚Äôt understand how to get it back‚Ä¶Everybody makes mistakes, everybody really messes up sometimes and this is a song that I wrote from the perspective of a 17-year-old boy. I‚Äôve always loved that in music you can kinda slip into different identities and you can sing from other people‚Äôs perspectives. So that‚Äôs what I did on this one‚Äìand I named all the characters in this story after my friends' kids."

genius_description:
‚ÄúNobody‚Äôs Love‚Äù is American pop-rock band Maroon 5‚Äôs first song of 2020 and serves as the second single for their upcoming sixth studio album.

The song is a revamped sound from the band‚Äôs fifth studio album, V, which was released in August 2014. The instrumental of it consists of light drums and harmonized electric guitars and a blending synth keyboard.

Lyrically, the song was inspired by the tough times in the world that were going on at the time of its release: the COVID-19 pandemic and the Black Lives Matter protests. The band‚Äôs lead singer Adam Levine explained the inspiration of the song through an Instagram post and claimed the song‚Äôs intention was to give love and hope to the listener about the tough times. This can be read in the Q&A below.

Healthcare workers fall into a routine of taking on shifts that can last anywhere from twelve hours to even forty-eight hours. ‚Äúmy future‚Äù portrays Billie reflecting on her past and her future, and her change in style from a more melancholic sound, towards a happier, more optimistic one.

‚Äúmy future‚Äù is Billie Eilish‚Äôs first single since the release of her acclaimed February 2020 James Bond theme song ‚ÄúNo Time To Die.‚Äù After almost a month away from social media, Eilish returned on July 24, 2020, to announce the track and its release date. The cover art and exact time of release for the song were announced later on July 28, 2020.

On July 29, a day before the release date, a snippet of the song was published on Billie‚Äôs Instagram page.

The track was released alongside a music video on July 30, 2020.

There‚Äôs nothing that talks about being alone is really powerful and you grow a lot and you learn a lot and it‚Äôs not bad.

Billie struggled with severe separation anxiety during her childhood to the point that one of her parents constantly had to be around her. genius_description:
‚ÄúThe Plan‚Äù is Travis Scott‚Äôs first track made specifically for a movie ‚Äî being a part of the 2020 film Tenet.

Tenet saw many issues and delays before it‚Äôs release (eventually being delayed indefinitely due to the coronavirus pandemic of 2020), but director Christopher Nolan told GQ that Scott‚Äôs contribution was ‚Äú‚Ä¶the final piece of a yearlong puzzle.‚Äù

The film finally released on August 21 internationally and September 3 in the United States.

The song was teased by the NBA on TNT on August 18, 2020 and later debuted on TNT‚Äôs broadcast of the Clippers versus Mavericks game on August 21.
genius_annotations:
[('Skrrt, skrrt in the ‚ÄôVert, skrrt, skrrt', [['‚Äú‚ÄòVert‚Äù is a slang contraction used for ‚Äúconvertible,‚Äù a type of passenger automobile that allows the roof to be retracted and stored at will, allowing the driver and passengers with an open-cabin experience.



Robert Downey Jr. in Iron Man 2 (2010) -- ¬© Marvel Entertainment


The ‚Äúskrrt‚Äù‚Äôs could refer to the sound of tires squealing, which are common in action movies and their high-speed car chase and race scenes. In the film Tenet, is one such scene, even though The Protagonist drives a 2010 Saab 9-5, a luxury vehicle that is not a convertible. The term still may have been used to make the rhyme.



John David Washington in Tenet (2020) ¬© 2020 -- Warner Bros. Pictures


Scott‚Äôs use of the word ‚Äúskrrt‚Äù hints at the inversion mechanics found within the film in both beginning and ending the lyric with the same word.']]), ('Close the opera', [['The opera Scott is referring to is the location of the first scene of Tenet. In it, The Protagonist is part of a SWAT operation to capture a strange artifact during a terrorist takeover at an opera.



Tenet (2020) ¬© 2020 -- Warner Bros. Pictures


The word ‚Äòopera‚Äô is also the fourth word of Sator Square, the five-word Latin palindrome, a two-dimensional table in which all the words can be read either up or down, or from left to right or right to left, but not diagonally.



***SPOILER ALERT***

This palindrome is also the foundation in which the film works:

  
"Rotas" is the name of the international security company: Rotas Security.  

"Opera" is the literal opera scene in the beginning of the film.  
"Tenet" is the name of the film as well as the organization that deals with the inversion technology. It is also at this point that the palindrome works backwards, i.e., the first two words and half of this word are read backwards.  
"Arepo" is the name of an art forger whose drawing is used in a blackmail trade with Kat and Andrei for their son.  
"Sator" is the last name of Andrei, the film's antagonist.']]), ('Last time I did the whippets', [['Whippets is another name for nitrous oxide gas. Nitrous oxide is a colourless gas that is commonly used for sedation and pain relief, but is also used by people to feel intoxicated or high.

Nitrous oxide is classified as a dissociative anaesthetic and has been found to produce dissociation of the mind from the body (a sense of floating), distorted perceptions and in rare cases, visual hallucinations.

The gas is inhaled, typically by discharging nitrous gas cartridges (bulbs or whippets) into another object, such as a balloon, or directly into the mouth. Inhaling nitrous oxide produces a rapid rush of euphoria and feeling of floating or excitement for a short period of time.

Other names:
Laughing gas, nitro, N2O, NOS, nangs, whippet, hippy crack, buzz bomb, balloons.']]), ('Hear the red and blue outside, I think our option‚Äôs up', [["‚ÄúRed and blue‚Äù is another way of referring to police, since police cars vehicles have a red and blue lights that flash on top of them to grab people‚Äôs attention.



Travis similarly used the term on his verse on the Migos‚Äò January 2017 track, ‚ÄúKelly Price,‚Äù where he raps:

Treat the Bentley truck like a Jag'
Got the red and blues on my ass




This is also a reference to the film Tenet, in which parts of the film feature a rooms with strong red and blue lighting respectively.



John David Washington and Robert Pattinson in Tenet (2020). ¬© 2020 ‚Äì Warner Bros. Pictures

***SPOILER ALERT***

In the film, the first scene in which The Protagonist witnesses the inversion technology being used is in this red and blue room. ‚ÄúOur option‚Äôs up‚Äù could refer to The Protagonist using the inversion device to save Kat since just before she was shot with an inverted bullet, hoping inverting her will reverse the inverted bullet‚Äôs damage. Everyone but The Protagonist believes she will die no matter what, but The Protagonist sees this opportunity as the only option to at least try and save her.

The Tenet organization uses these two colors to help organize their operations when dealing with inverted people. Red tags are given to members who are traveling forward in time with the world they are in while blue tags are given to members who are inverted and operating at the same time as the red team."]]), ('What is wild, let it be, ragers out, gotta eat (Yeah)', [['Travis considers his fanbase ‚Äúragers‚Äù‚Äîhe often uses the term to address his fans while performing. Scott took inspiration from Kid Cudi‚Äôs alter-ego, Mr. Rager, to come up with the name‚Äîhe‚Äôs been using it since the release of August 2014‚Äôs Days Before Rodeo.  Moreover, Travis tattoed the term across the side of his hand in February 2019.

When Travis says that it‚Äôs time for his fans to ‚Äúeat,‚Äù he is indicating that he‚Äôll be dropping new music for his fans to hear. This phrase was used while promoting his October 2019 chart-topping single, ‚ÄúHIGHEST IN THE ROOM.‚Äù In an interview with Zane Lowe, he said:

But I‚Äôm always down to drop music and serve some packs to the fans. It‚Äôs time for the fans to eat.']]), ('Ride on land, Boeing jet, make it land', [['In the film Tenet, a Boeing 747 is crashed and blown up in a scene on land. Due to the popular and often over-used method of creating computer-generated special effects in Hollywood films, it was assumed this much-talked about action sequence that was teased in the film‚Äôs second trailer would follow suit. Visionary director Christopher Nolan is known for his unique level of practicality, particularly with the hallway fight scene from 2010‚Äôs Inception.

Carrying on this tradition of practicality, Nolan purchased and blew up a Boeing 747 since it was cheaper than hiring a visual effects team to create it artificially. In lead star John David Washington‚Äôs words:

That was a real plane, and that was a real building that they crashed that plane into. And we, cast and crew, all witnessed it. It was epic! It was incredible, we all cheered and hurrayed and hurrahed when they yelled cut after Chris felt like he got it. What you saw is really what happened ‚Äì at least the night I was there.

On August 26, 2020, Warner Bros. Pictures posted a special behind-the-scenes video for the film to promote its American release the following week, focusing on this scene for the last third of the short featurette.

https://youtu.be/u0hCSxqnjT0?t=405']])]

genius_description:
‚ÄúThe Voice‚Äù is a track from Chicago rapper Lil Durk, serving as the lead single to his upcoming untitled sixth studio album. The official music video was released on September 4, 2020, alongside the track.

On this song, Lil Durk reminisces on his old life in the streets in a sad tone, dropping lines about sexual activity, legal issues, and weapons. While rapping on the two verses, Durk sings with a robotic auto-tune on the chorus.

Lil Durk teased the existence of this song, in early May 2020, when he changed his Twitter name to ‚ÄúTHE VOICE.‚Äù He then ultimately announced the song‚Äôs release date via Twitter on August 28, 2020.

genius_description:
The first track off of Big Sean‚Äôs fifth studio album, Detroit 2, is a proud declaration against his haters.

Big Sean, who signed with G.O.O.D. Music in 2007 and released his debut album Finally Famous in 2011, has been at the top of the rap game for nearly a decade, and wants to make it clear that he has no intent of stopping or slowing down.

In an interview with Vulture about Detroit 2, he said:

[Criticism] isn‚Äôt something I think about every day. I don‚Äôt feel like I have to prove myself. That‚Äôs not what I‚Äôm thinking about. I‚Äôm thinking more like, I gotta offer something that people need. That‚Äôs where I am lately, where my mind has been with the music I‚Äôve been making now.
genius_annotations:
[('Next episode, got the whole fucking world watching
 I might leave the series, come back like I‚Äôm Rodman', [['Sean refers to this album as the ‚Äúnext episode‚Äù to the first Detroit mixtape, and he knows the world‚Äôs been anticipating it like it were the next episode in a television series.

Consistent with the television imagery, Sean uses a play on words to state that he might just leave and come back to this ‚Äúseries‚Äù like Dennis Rodman of the 1998 Bulls. By saying this, he‚Äôs saying that even if he were to take a break (from a television or playoff series) he would still bounce back with his A-game, as Rodman infamously did.

https://thecomeback.com/nba/that-time-dennis-rodman-skipped-a-1998-nba-finals-practice-to-attend-a-wcw-event-then-had-14-rebounds-shut-down-karl-malone-in-game-4.html']]), ('Red Wings jersey B.I.G., look like Pac
 The blacker the berry, more they wan‚Äô see it rot (Rot)', [["Big Sean reps for the Detroit Red Wings‚Äîan ice hockey team based in his hometown. In 1994, journalists captured an image of 2Pac leaving court in a Red Wings jersey, which has turned into a symbol of Detroit pride. In addition, Sean seems to be twisting a few lines from 2Pac‚Äôs October 1993 single, ‚ÄúKeep Ya Head Up‚Äù:

Some say the blacker the berry, the sweeter the juice
I say the darker the flesh, then the deeper the roots



From left to right: Big Sean, 2Pac, and The Spirit of Detroit in Red Wings jerseys.

The phrase ‚Äúthe blacker the berry‚Äù stems from Wallace Thurman‚Äôs 1929 novel of the same name. Sean uses the line to address racism‚Äîin  June 2020, protests were ignited by the killings of George Floyd, Breonna Taylor, and Ahmaud Arbery. Sean joined protesters in Los Angeles and opened up about partaking in protests on social media:

I don‚Äôt know if it‚Äôs to make us look like we wild beasts or don‚Äôt have control, but we clearly are not wild beasts. We‚Äôre extraordinary, talented magical people that if you took us out of the equation, the world would be very, very bland.

It‚Äôs also worth noting that Sean uses some clever wordplay by spelling out his rap name, ‚ÄúBig‚Äù Sean, to compare himself to The Notorious B.I.G., who feuded with 2Pac in 1995‚Äì1996. This is not the first time that Sean spells out his name‚Äîon YG‚Äôs 2018 track, ‚ÄúBIG BANK,‚Äù he says:

I said, ‚ÄòBitch, I'ma do me‚Äô
B.I.G., bitch everything zoomed-in (zoom)"]]), ('And they want me to stop but why would I stop?
 Huh? I am unstoppable
 Hold up, why would I stop?
 Bitch, why would I stop?
 Chill (Chill), chill
 I don‚Äôt jump, I dive in it
 Hold up, hold up, hold up
 This the reason I‚Äôm alive, ain‚Äôt it?', [['Detroit 2 marks a decade long career for Big Sean. In an industry where artists come and go quickly, Sean proudly boasts his longevity and success in the rap game.

Because of his success, Sean knows that there‚Äôs no reason for him to take his foot off the gas, which compels him to ask: ‚ÄúWhy would I stop?‚Äù



The idiom ‚Äújump ship‚Äù means to quickly leave when things go wrong. Because of his fame and success, Big Sean is probably facing a lot of pressure to keep on producing quality work. If anybody else were faced with this same pressure, they would ‚Äújump‚Äù, just as someone may ‚Äújump ship‚Äù.

However, because of Big Sean‚Äôs drive and work ethic, he chooses to ‚Äúdive in it‚Äù, rather than jump. This indicates how Sean faces his problems head-on, and full of confidence because he knows he will come out on top. It‚Äôs because of this work ethic that he is still alive, referring to his actual life and his career‚Äôs longevity.']]), ('And I do this shit for the family (Straight up)
 Yeah, that‚Äôs just the roots I had planted (On God)', [['Building off the last few lines where he talks about having a family, Big Sean states that everything he does in his career and life is for his family.

He uses a metaphor to compare his family to the roots of a tree, which serve two functions: they provide nutrients for growth, and they provide support to hold the tree steady in place.

He also uses a homophone to establish a play on words, using the phrase ‚Äúplanned it‚Äù. Sean states this is just how he ‚Äúplanned it‚Äù, referring to making his family a priority in life. ‚ÄúPlanned it‚Äù also sounds like ‚Äúplanted‚Äù, referring to Big Sean planting the seeds of success that will eventually turn into roots and then into a prosperous family tree.']]), ('Hero in my hood, when they dress like me, that‚Äôs cosplay', [['Big Sean acknowledges that he is looked up to in Detroit as a hero for all of the work and money he‚Äôs invested into his city.

Cosplay is a performance art in which participants wear costumes and fashion accessories to represent a specific character, usually superheroes. Being a hero in his hood of Detroit, there are going to be kids who look up to him and try to be him, like cosplayers.']]), ('I can‚Äôt be handin‚Äô out samples (No way)

 That shit sound like a job, not a family (Straight up)', [['Big Sean is at a point in his life where he cannot keep fucking around with ‚Äúlil ho‚Äôs‚Äù because he knows the consequences.

‚ÄúHanding out samples‚Äù, is a double entendre. The first meaning refers to having multiple partners, who each get a ‚Äúsample‚Äù, or just a taste of what it would be like to be with Big Sean. The second meaning may refer to sperm, or children, because Big Sean does not want to give his seed (a sample of Big Sean himself) to just any woman.

By giving out these samples to multiple women, he will end up with multiple children. This does not sound like the ideal life for Sean, because he knows this will result in a lot of baby mama drama, child support claims, and hella stress.

https://bckonline.com/2020/07/23/dmx-shouts-out-to-all-the-mothers-of-his-15-kids-during-verzuz-battle/']]), ('I‚Äôm at the point if I fuck with a lil‚Äô ho
 It‚Äôs not just a fling, it‚Äôs a scandal (On God)', [['At this point in his career, Big Sean always has eyes on him. Because of this, media outlets like TMZ or The Shade Room are quick to make a scandal out of Sean‚Äôs relationship with any woman, whether it‚Äôs wife or side piece, for likes and views on their platform. This highlights just how far Big Sean has come, and how famous he is at this point in his career.



In a podcast episode of Broken Record with Rick Rubin, Andr√© 3000 states that he misses the days where he could just take a stroll in the city with a pretty lady. However, because of his fame, he can no longer do that without the internet blowing up with speculations and theories about who this woman may be, despite the fact that it‚Äôs not that serious to begin with. Big Sean now faces similar problems.']]), ('My dawg on the same way, the mode is attack', [['Being the first track off of Detroit 2, Big Sean is coming correct by being in ‚Äúattack mode‚Äù, and he is playing offensively, not defensively. His ‚Äúdawg‚Äù is the ‚Äúsame way‚Äù.

Since ‚Äúdawg‚Äù is slang for homie, Sean could be referring to his friend who is ready to take the offensive with Sean.

On ‚ÄúMr. Right Now,‚Äù 21 Savage and Drake trade bars about introducing their women to luxury lifestyles and boasting their respective sexual prowess. They drop references to multiple R&B staples, including TLC, Keith Sweat, and SZA.

21 Savage has often expressed his love for R&B. He frequently covers songs by legendary and modern R&B artists on his Instagram story.

Metro Boomin provides a melodic instrumental built around a carnivalesque sample.
genius_annotations:
[('We in quarantine (On God), but my M‚Äôs long (On God)', [['When this song was released, the world was in the midst of the coronavirus pandemic. This negatively affected the financial situations of millions of people around the world, particularly Americans. Initially, people were encouraged to quarantine themselves within their homes in an effort to hopefully protect them and others from contracting the virus.

Entertainers, like Savage, were forced to postpone or cancel their concerts and tours due to regulations restricting or prohibiting large gatherings of people. However, Savage indicates that these restrictions did not limit or stop his inflow of wealth. As of this song‚Äôs release, Savage‚Äôs net worth is approximated at over $12 million and is still growing.

Moreover, Savage is the sole owner of his masters, allowing him to control a variety of financial and business situations involving his music or likeness.']]), ('Put you in Chanel, I‚Äôma teach you how to stunt (21)', [["Chanel is a luxurious French brand that sells expensive clothes and fashion accessories. Savage mentions the brand in another SAVAGE MODE II track, ‚ÄúRich Nigga Shit‚Äù:

My bitches be askin', ‚ÄúWhere‚Äôs Chanel at?‚Äù

Savage, himself, is often pictured wearing the brand:



Savage wearing orange Chanel hip-tops"]]), ('I‚Äôma slide anytime you want', [['‚ÄúSlide,‚Äù in this context, means to meet with someone and have sex. Savage also used the term in a more literal way on his December 2018 song, ‚Äúasmr‚Äù:

Slide in and out (Out)
Spend the night? I doubt (Doubt)']]), ('But she stay in apartments I got beef at (On God)
 Pussy so good, I had to sneak back (On God)
 Hit her with my Glizzy, boy, I keep that', [['‚ÄúGlizzy‚Äù is slang for a Glock. A Glock is an Austrian made semi-automatic pistol that‚Äôs popular among many law enforcement and government agencies.

Though Savage is making a correlation between his gun and his male genitalia, it connects with the other two lines; since he‚Äôs in enemy territory, he keeps a Glock for protection.']]), ('Threw my heart out the window, feelings gone (21)
 Threw my heart out the window, but', [["Savage has rapped about not having a heart before on his July 2016 song, ‚ÄúNo Heart‚Äù:

I grew up in the streets without no heart
I‚Äôm prayin' to my Glock and my carbon

Savage being ‚Äúheartless‚Äù likely comes from all of the violence and trauma he has endured over the years. His brother, Tayman, was killed in a botched drug deal, and on his 21st birthday, during an attempted robbery, his best friend, Johnny, was shot and killed. Savage was also shot six times."]]), ('She want me to fuck her to some Keith Sweat (21)', [['Keith Sweat is an R&B singer who rose to fame in the late ‚Äò80s. He has several top ten Billboard hits, all which includes his June 1996 song, ‚ÄúNobody‚Äù and his September 1996 song, ‚ÄúTwisted.‚Äù Savage furthers the song‚Äôs theme of his girl wanting to make love to R&B music.

Savage and Keith are friends: they did a RapCaviar sit-down together in November 2017 and appeared in a skit together.']]), ('Ayy, turn your phone off, take your clothes off (21)

However, Savage doesn‚Äôt want any extra ties to this girl; he just wants sex. He made this clear in the February 2019 video version of ‚Äúa lot,‚Äù where he raps about not wanting to be married:

Be a married man, right now I just can‚Äôt']]), ('(Metro)', [['This is one of Metro Boomin‚Äôs many producer tags. This tag is voiced by Young Thug and comes from his November 2015 song, ‚ÄúHercules.‚Äù

The tag, though rarely used, can be heard on songs like Gunna‚Äôs February 2018 song, ‚ÄúCar Sick,‚Äù and Nicki Minaj‚Äôs August 2018 song, ‚ÄúChun Swae.‚Äù']]), ('While I jump inside that box and have a field day

 And my goal is to get you to the finish line', [['‚ÄúBox‚Äù is slang for a woman‚Äôs vagina and ‚Äúhave a field day‚Äù is an idiom that means to get pleasure from doing something‚Äîin this instance, having sexual intercourse.

A ‚Äústroke‚Äù is an action that‚Äôs done during intercourse where a male enters, then nearly exits his partner in slow, repetitive motions. Drake previously mentioned the sexual move on the February 2019 remix of Summer Walker song, ‚ÄúGirls Need Love‚Äù:

Lastly, Drake getting his girl to the ‚Äúfinish line‚Äù likely means he‚Äôs gonna make her orgasm.']]), ('Make that thing sing like Sade (21)', [['Sade is a Grammy-winning British band that‚Äôs named after their lead singer, Sade Adu. She‚Äôs known for her soulful ballads about love and loss. Additionally, she‚Äôs one of the most successful British female artists of all time and has had a big influence on contemporary music.
